<DOC><DOCNO> AP880318-0306 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0855EST</FILEID><FIRST>a f BC-RetailTakeovers Adv21   03-18 0869</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Retail Takeovers, Adv 21,0906</SECOND><NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Editions Monday March 21</NOTE><HEAD>Getting the Wagons in a Circle To Fend Off Takeovers</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Running a retailing company has become adefensive business these days.   Time was, all management had to worry about was getting peoplein the front door. Now, they have to fend off corporate raiders atthe back door.   With takeover activity threatening their independence, somecompanies have taken steps to protect themselves. But others stillcling to the myth that it can't happen here.   Two weeks ago, Dart Group Corp. dropped its bid for Stop andamp; ShopCos. after Stop andamp; Shop agreed to a leveraged buyout by KohlbergKravis Roberts Inc. Analysts expect Dart, with a string ofunsuccessful takeover attempts behind it, to try for anotherretailer.   And if Campeau Corp. loses to R.H. Macy andamp; Co. Inc. in theirbattle over Federated Department Stores Inc., the Toronto-baseddeveloper will probably pursue another major department storeoperator such as May Department Stores Co. or Dayton Hudson Corp.   Which retailers are the most likely targets?   The most vulnerable are companies whose stock is widely held,rather than concentrated in the hands of a few insiders, saidMonroe H. Greenstein, a retail industry analyst with the investmentfirm Bear Stearns andamp; Co. Inc.   Out of hundreds of publicly-liste       50  30      cdyAustin                 60  37 1.94   clrBaltimore              47  29      cdyBillings               45  31       clrBirmingham             62  45 .08  cdyBismarck               40  22      cdyBoise                  55  32       clrBoston                 53  34      snBrownsville            74  46 .11   clrBuffalo            